00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:47.080
It's a very, very,
very fast process.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:49.600
It's really remarkable
to me that this

00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:51.530
combines so many
photlithographic steps

00:01:51.530 --> 00:01:54.220
that if you wanted to
make this in the lab using

00:01:54.220 --> 00:01:57.010
photlithography, and
condenses these six or seven

00:01:57.010 --> 00:01:59.190
steps into one process.

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:00.860
So it's pretty remarkable.

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:03.630
So DuPont, the people who
made the pace-- so we used

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:07.630
PV16A if you guys are curious
for our front contacts

00:02:07.630 --> 00:02:08.961
for silver paste.

00:02:08.961 --> 00:02:10.919
And we actually get--
the really important part

00:02:10.919 --> 00:02:13.089
is this peaking
temperature, and you

00:02:13.089 --> 00:02:15.380
can see we actually got pretty
close to the ramp times.

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:18.680
Where it really starts
to deviate is here,

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:22.690
and we hold it around 400,
a little bit longer, which

00:02:22.690 --> 00:02:25.540
is several reasons for that, and
I'll go into that in a second.

00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:27.990
But what's important
is that all these are

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:29.650
fired in an oxygen atmosphere.

00:02:29.650 --> 00:02:31.420
So normally in
these belt furnaces,

00:02:31.420 --> 00:02:33.920
and this is again what's used
in industry-- this is actually

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:36.720
the same exact tool
that I use at Harvard--

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:39.390
it actually looks like this with
the giant CRT monitor on top.

00:02:39.390 --> 00:02:41.270
The only way to get the data
off is with a three and a half

00:02:41.270 --> 00:02:42.076
floppy drive.

00:02:42.076 --> 00:02:43.450
I can't tell you
how difficult it

00:02:43.450 --> 00:02:45.930
was to find a working three
and a half floppy drive.

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:47.380
Most of them are
demagnetized at this point.

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:48.330
I had to buy new ones.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:49.420
They're still being
made, by the way.

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:50.753
If you want them, go to Staples.

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:56.300
So anyhow, it's done in
an oxygen atmosphere,

00:02:56.300 --> 00:03:00.030
so they generally force airflow
into these giant belt furnaces,

00:03:00.030 --> 00:03:01.230
and these are really long.

00:03:01.230 --> 00:03:03.380
Like that's probably
about a foot

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:05.690
wide, maybe 18 inches wide.

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:10.220
So this goes on for tens
of feet, or several meters,

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:12.250
depending on where you're from.

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:14.510
And it's done an oxygen
atmosphere, an air atmosphere,

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:17.445
because it needs to burn
off a lot of the binders

00:03:17.445 --> 00:03:19.570
and some of the organics
that might still be there.

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:21.944
And so those organics burn
off, and what you're left with

00:03:21.944 --> 00:03:26.410
are the little metal particles,
the frit, and some metal oxide

00:03:26.410 --> 00:03:26.910
glass.

00:03:26.910 --> 00:03:29.430
It's usually lead oxide,
although DuPont will never

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:33.040
tell you, but from
papers I've read

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:36.690
this is generally what's used.

00:03:36.690 --> 00:03:39.930
So when that happens-- this
is that burn-off period.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.414
When it spikes, the
frit will actually

00:03:42.414 --> 00:03:44.080
burn through your
silicon nitride layer.

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:45.954
You guys didn't have a
silicon nitride layer,

00:03:45.954 --> 00:03:48.262
but if it was there, it
would help eat through it.

00:03:48.262 --> 00:03:50.220
And so that way, you've
removed the dielectrics

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:53.460
so you can actually make metal
contact with your silicon

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:55.880
surface underneath.

00:03:55.880 --> 00:04:00.400
That firing will-- during
that peak also simultaneously,

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:02.850
these middle particles
will melt and form

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:05.710
this triple eutectic point
with the silicon underneath it.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.790
And so the triple comes from
the silver, the silicon,

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:09.342
and the lead.

00:04:09.342 --> 00:04:11.440
The lead actually
dissociates from the glass.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:13.810
This lowers the melting
temperature of that mixture,

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:16.130
and you can make good ohmic
contact with the surface.

00:04:16.130 --> 00:04:18.720
So it's actually a pretty
remarkable, incredible process.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.380
It's still almost
kind of magic to me

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:22.560
on how the whole thing
works, and a lot of it's

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:24.972
just kind of guess and check
and still very proprietary.

00:04:24.972 --> 00:04:26.930
So the science is still
a little lacking there.

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:30.430
You don't find a lot of
good articles explaining

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:31.180
the science of it.

00:04:31.180 --> 00:04:32.846
I have a few if you
guys are interested.

00:04:32.846 --> 00:04:36.381
NREL's put out a lot of really
interesting stuff, and some

00:04:36.381 --> 00:04:37.880
of the ways they
actually figure out

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:40.540
the actual profile underneath
the contacts versus you

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:43.690
measure the temperature on
the side of the contacts,

00:04:43.690 --> 00:04:47.840
so actually touching the silicon
or the silicon nitride surface,

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:51.150
is you actually measure hydrogen
diffusion underneath it.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:53.530
And so they'll actually
etch off the contacts

00:04:53.530 --> 00:04:57.110
and using secondary ion
mass spectroscopy measure

00:04:57.110 --> 00:04:59.531
the hydrogen concentration
off the contact

00:04:59.531 --> 00:05:01.530
and underneath the contact,
and that'll actually

00:05:01.530 --> 00:05:04.280
tell you what temperature it
saw based on that diffusion

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:05.100
profile.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:07.230
So there is some good
science going on,

00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:11.080
but there's not a lot
of great papers on it.

00:05:11.297 --> 00:05:12.880
So anyhow, that just
kind of gives you

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:14.505
what I was working
on over the weekend,

00:05:14.505 --> 00:05:16.100
trying to get these cells fired.

00:05:16.100 --> 00:05:18.940
So I aggregated a
lot of the results

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:21.464
and tried to make sense
of what was going on.

00:05:21.464 --> 00:05:23.880
I think I showed some of you
different firing temperatures

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:25.050
and the fill factors
that we got and there

00:05:25.050 --> 00:05:28.150
was kind of just noisy data, so
I couldn't get any real trends.

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:31.219
The best trend I could
find was that if you

00:05:31.219 --> 00:05:33.260
take the median of all
the short-circuit currents

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:34.430
of the cells and
you look at the ones

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:36.100
with four millimeter and
two millimeter spacing,

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:38.220
the four millimeter spacing
has a slightly higher

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:39.994
short-circuit
current, presumably

00:05:39.994 --> 00:05:40.910
due to shading losses.

00:05:40.910 --> 00:05:42.950
If you look at the relative
areas that each of these

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:44.658
cover up, you would
expect a 4% increase.

00:05:44.658 --> 00:05:48.440
This is about 3%, so
I'll take that as fact.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:50.717
It's certainly within
the noise and the error

00:05:50.717 --> 00:05:52.300
of the number of
samples that we have,

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:55.730
but I thought it was
interesting nonetheless.

00:05:55.730 --> 00:05:58.090
Additionally, I plotted
the series resistance

00:05:58.090 --> 00:06:01.110
that I calculated from
your dark IV curves

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:02.854
and plotted your maximum power.

00:06:02.854 --> 00:06:04.770
I also removed all the
cells that were broken.

00:06:04.770 --> 00:06:06.437
I'm sure if I actually
normalized them--

00:06:06.437 --> 00:06:08.228
some of the cells that
were broken actually

00:06:08.228 --> 00:06:10.650
performed a lot better,
and I'll get into maybe why

00:06:10.650 --> 00:06:13.492
that was the case in a second.

00:06:13.492 --> 00:06:14.950
But really the
take-home message is

00:06:14.950 --> 00:06:16.825
that our really best
performing cells are all

00:06:16.825 --> 00:06:18.300
clumped over here.

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:22.290
And so you can see that our best
cells have a very low series

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:22.915
resistance.

00:06:22.915 --> 00:06:24.040
That's not always the case.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:25.790
There's some outliers,
like this guy here,

00:06:25.790 --> 00:06:28.869
and I don't know
how that happened.

00:06:28.869 --> 00:06:30.660
So some really interesting
things going on,

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:32.500
and I'm still trying
to sift through it.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:34.874
So I talked about
this I think yesterday

00:06:34.874 --> 00:06:37.040
in the analysis section,
but there's several sources

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:37.980
of series resistance.

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:41.033
Any of you guys familiar
with what they are?

00:06:41.033 --> 00:06:44.327
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] resistance
and emitter sheet resistance.

00:06:44.327 --> 00:06:46.285
PROFESSOR: Emitter sheet
resistance, and then--

00:06:46.285 --> 00:06:47.590
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:49.480
PROFESSOR: So there's line
resistance along the fingers

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:50.480
and then there's
contact resistance,

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:52.760
so I'm going to draw
this out really quickly.

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:55.915
So if you have--
this is your emitter.

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:03.080
You have a contact here
and a contact here.

00:07:05.690 --> 00:07:11.430
If you generate an electron
here, it'll diffuse,

00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:13.450
hit the junction.

00:07:13.450 --> 00:07:16.029
Then it has to flow through
the emitter to the contact.

00:07:16.029 --> 00:07:17.820
There's an associated
resistance with that.

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:19.870
That's the series
resistance that we

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:22.510
taught in class that has to do
with the emitter resistance.

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:25.571
Additionally to hop over that
metal semiconductor junction,

00:07:25.571 --> 00:07:27.070
there's actually a
resistance there.

00:07:27.070 --> 00:07:28.528
That's called a
contact resistance.

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:45.010
So this is emitter and
this is our contact,

00:07:45.010 --> 00:07:48.304
and then it has to travel from
the line to the busbar here,

00:07:48.304 --> 00:07:49.595
and that's our line resistance.

00:07:55.177 --> 00:07:56.760
And I think what's
really limiting us,

00:07:56.760 --> 00:08:02.182
because when I looked at both
the shallow and deep emitters,

00:08:02.182 --> 00:08:03.640
the series resistance
didn't really

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:05.579
have any noticeable trends.

00:08:05.579 --> 00:08:08.120
So I really think that this is
what's limiting us completely,

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:11.752
is our contact resistance,
which is kind of too bad.

00:08:11.752 --> 00:08:13.460
So one of the reasons
I think that that's

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:15.810
the case additionally
is that the cells

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:19.497
that performed the best-- I know
Joel's did particularly well.

00:08:19.497 --> 00:08:20.580
What was your fill factor?

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:21.270
Do you remember?

00:08:21.270 --> 00:08:24.596
AUDIENCE: Well, on the one side
it was 0.5, and on the other

00:08:24.596 --> 00:08:26.470
it was 0.64.

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:28.290
PROFESSOR: OK, so
one side was better.

00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:31.252
So again, the inhomogeneity
of doing the measurement

00:08:31.252 --> 00:08:33.460
is also another indication
that our series resistance

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:36.630
across the contacts
is really poor.

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:39.760
So some of the other
contacts if you look on the--

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:43.151
where's my good piece of chalk?

00:08:43.151 --> 00:08:43.650
Right.

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:47.820
If here's our busbar, some
people saw delamination.

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:49.600
Who saw their
contacts delaminated?

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:51.380
Yeah, so a couple people.

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:53.940
And so what that means is
that these contacts actually

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:58.010
peeled up, and that's usually
showing that the-- what's

00:08:58.010 --> 00:09:02.020
funny, though, is that
these areas in the middle

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:02.800
didn't delaminate.

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:05.580
It was only the edges
here, and so that's

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:08.370
showing that some parts
are being properly fired

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:11.887
and some parts are
being underfired

00:09:11.887 --> 00:09:13.720
because when I fired
at higher temperatures,

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:15.110
I was getting shunting.

00:09:15.110 --> 00:09:17.810
And that was due to shunting
through the center area.

00:09:17.810 --> 00:09:21.230
So I think that the RTA
that I was using-- this

00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:23.870
wasn't the case on some of the
earlier cells I had processed,

00:09:23.870 --> 00:09:26.480
but is rather
inhomogeneous in terms

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:30.244
of the temperature profile
it's delivering to our cells.

00:09:30.244 --> 00:09:32.493
So I think that could be
part of our problem, as well.

00:09:32.493 --> 00:09:34.910
AUDIENCE: How many cells did
he fire up at the same time?

00:09:34.910 --> 00:09:35.860
Just one, or--

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:37.871
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
it's one at a time,

00:09:37.871 --> 00:09:40.370
and there's some variability
in the peak firing temperature.

00:09:42.867 --> 00:09:44.450
So I've learned a
lot about when we're

00:09:44.450 --> 00:09:48.310
going to buy an RTA for
our lab, what to look for.

00:09:48.310 --> 00:09:49.980
The temporal
resolution of the data

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:53.500
you get out of it and how it
records it is 0.6 seconds.

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:56.080
And when this thing's
ramping at 100 C per second,

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:58.484
your variability is quite large.

00:09:58.484 --> 00:10:00.900
So the temperature I read is
not just from the data point,

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:03.150
but I do a linear interpolation
to actually figure out

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:07.600
what the peak is on
both sides of that peak,

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:10.150
and it ends up being about
anywhere from 20 to 40

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:13.660
degrees Celsius higher
using that technique.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:17.050
And so the variability varies.

00:10:17.050 --> 00:10:18.960
It's about 20
degrees plus or minus

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:21.770
10 degrees Celsius in terms
of what I want the peak to be

00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:23.910
and what it actually is.

00:10:23.910 --> 00:10:27.490
So the RTA that we're using now
is not incredibly reputable.

00:10:27.490 --> 00:10:30.130
Also, better RTAs will
have a different heater

00:10:30.130 --> 00:10:32.620
on top and bottom, and
so you can actually

00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:34.250
heat one side more
than the other.

00:10:34.250 --> 00:10:40.160
And generally belt furnaces,
so commercial ones,

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:42.840
will have that same
kind of control.

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:46.780
I know at 1366, they've
actually done optimization

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:48.906
to do heating the top
and bottom differently

00:10:48.906 --> 00:10:51.280
because they use different
pace, they have different heat

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:53.225
requirements,
thermal requirements.

00:10:53.225 --> 00:10:55.770
And so nailing that
temperature and that profile

00:10:55.770 --> 00:10:58.025
actually takes a lot of
iteration and a lot of time.

00:10:58.025 --> 00:11:00.780
And it's really just learning
the tell as opposed to,

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:02.460
the again, good
science behind it.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:07.270
So it can be rather difficult
and time-consuming to do.

00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:10.242
So that's what I have
to say about the cells.

00:11:10.242 --> 00:11:12.450
I think overall, though, I
think the efficiencies are

00:11:12.450 --> 00:11:15.250
on the order of 6% to I think
9% for some of the cells,

00:11:15.250 --> 00:11:18.660
so that's not too bad.

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:21.850
I'm still rather
pleased with that.

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:24.927
Last time I think
Tonio stopped right

00:11:24.927 --> 00:11:27.260
before he was going to talk
about performance of modules

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:31.710
in the field and kind
of what's the difference

00:11:31.710 --> 00:11:35.070
between your cell efficiency
and your module efficiency.

