00:17:14.846 --> 00:17:16.130
AUDIENCE: Super bandgap.

00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:17.250
PROFESSOR: Super bandgap.

00:17:17.250 --> 00:17:20.130
So what could be happening is
our bandgap could be changing.

00:17:20.130 --> 00:17:23.050
I sub L, as Ben pointed
out, should increase

00:17:23.050 --> 00:17:26.829
the flux of photons
above the bandgap,

00:17:26.829 --> 00:17:30.940
and EG actually decreases
the temperature.

00:17:30.940 --> 00:17:33.730
So your bandgap actually
usually increases--

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:35.946
the true bandgap of
silicon defined--

00:17:35.946 --> 00:17:37.320
most properties
of semiconductors

00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:39.864
are actually
defined at 0 Kelvin,

00:17:39.864 --> 00:17:41.280
and semiconductors
are technically

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:43.790
insulators because they
don't conduct electricity

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:45.142
at 0 Kelvin.

00:17:45.142 --> 00:17:47.350
That just means semiconductor
is a class of materials

00:17:47.350 --> 00:17:50.870
that have a small enough bandgap
that they can thermally promote

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:53.370
carriers that they can actually
conduct some electricity

00:17:53.370 --> 00:17:54.970
at room temperature.

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:57.900
But the true bandgap of
silicon's around 1.17.

00:17:57.900 --> 00:17:59.630
And as you increase
temperature, you

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:01.030
get a reduction of the bandgap.

00:18:01.030 --> 00:18:03.279
And so what should happen
is your ISC should increase,

00:18:03.279 --> 00:18:06.060
but only very, very slightly.

00:18:06.060 --> 00:18:10.750
So if you go over the derivation
for the actual decrease

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:14.520
in the overall efficiency,
there's a few things.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:19.950
One, remember your
maximum power is

00:18:19.950 --> 00:18:22.630
your Voc times your ISC
times your fill factor.

00:18:22.630 --> 00:18:24.730
So if you want the
derivative of your max power

00:18:24.730 --> 00:18:26.596
with respect to
temperature, you need

00:18:26.596 --> 00:18:28.470
to do the partial
derivatives and sum them up

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:30.053
for all of those
different components.

00:18:30.053 --> 00:18:33.600
So that's what this
calculation's doing.

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:36.540
And again, this is what
it is for fill factor.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.880
This is all in Martin
Green's paper down here

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:41.960
and also on PVCDROM if you
guys are interested in that.

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:45.230
Martin Green's
tabulated a lot of this,

00:18:45.230 --> 00:18:47.140
making these general
expressions and also

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:51.990
fitting it to experimental
data to get that information.

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:55.800
And then it ends up being
not a negligible percent,

00:18:55.800 --> 00:19:00.940
but about half a percent per
degree Celsius for silicon.

00:19:00.940 --> 00:19:03.160
So if you go up
by 40 degrees, you

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:07.985
can see that temperature's a
non-negligible effect in terms

00:19:07.985 --> 00:19:08.610
of performance.

