00:23:36.840 --> 00:23:39.026
is running in reverse bias.

00:23:39.026 --> 00:23:42.800
And when you're in reverse bias,
you're running a lot of current

00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:44.520
through your shunts.

00:23:44.520 --> 00:23:46.880
And for those who were
here this morning,

00:23:46.880 --> 00:23:48.630
we know that shunts
are really, really bad

00:23:48.630 --> 00:23:50.963
because that's where all your
current's running through.

00:23:50.963 --> 00:23:53.107
And if your current's
running through one localized

00:23:53.107 --> 00:23:54.940
spot, that's where it's
heating up the most,

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:57.106
and it can heat up to
temperatures that can actually

00:23:57.106 --> 00:23:59.750
melt the encapsulant or
completely destroy the cell,

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:01.700
so this can actually
be rather destructive.

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:07.750
And generally once your cells
are made and encapsulated

00:24:07.750 --> 00:24:12.230
in the module, it's really
hard to remove them and replace

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:12.730
that module.

00:24:12.730 --> 00:24:15.620
Pretty much the whole
module's kaput at that point,

00:24:15.620 --> 00:24:16.810
so it's pretty destructive.

00:24:16.810 --> 00:24:20.280
So what people
generally do for-- yeah?

00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:23.320
AUDIENCE: So in maintenance,
like yearly maintenance,

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:26.700
you should clean the
panel because of the dirt,

00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:31.560
or is there any other thing
that you should do [INAUDIBLE]?

00:24:31.560 --> 00:24:33.060
PROFESSOR: There's
important things.

00:24:33.060 --> 00:24:35.982
So you don't want--
it helps if they're

00:24:35.982 --> 00:24:38.550
angled so snow and other
things will fall off of it.

00:24:38.550 --> 00:24:40.520
You don't want to
put it in areas

00:24:40.520 --> 00:24:43.103
next to a chimney, for example,
where certain parts of the day

00:24:43.103 --> 00:24:47.810
it will be shaded,
or things like that.

00:24:47.810 --> 00:24:51.870
So I've seen some
studies on cleaning,

00:24:51.870 --> 00:24:54.080
and it all depends on if it
economically makes sense.

00:24:54.080 --> 00:24:56.132
If you want to pay someone
to clean your panels,

00:24:56.132 --> 00:24:56.840
that's expensive.

00:24:56.840 --> 00:24:59.710
Is it worth it for them
to do that if you're only

00:24:59.710 --> 00:25:00.802
saving just a little bit?

00:25:00.802 --> 00:25:03.260
Obviously, the shading's so
bad that it could detrimentally

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:04.470
ruin and destroy your module.

00:25:04.470 --> 00:25:07.420
It's really-- you
want to do that?

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:10.120
Ways to prevent the destruction
is actually a lot of cells

00:25:10.120 --> 00:25:12.470
will have bypass diodes.

00:25:12.470 --> 00:25:15.456
So if a string goes
down, the current

00:25:15.456 --> 00:25:17.080
will just [? flow ?]
through that diode

00:25:17.080 --> 00:25:20.790
and won't destroy the
cell, and so that's one way

00:25:20.790 --> 00:25:22.740
of kind of fixing that problem.

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:23.740
That's a great question.

00:25:29.980 --> 00:25:33.140
So now we're stacking
ourselves in parallel.

00:25:33.140 --> 00:25:35.380
Normally, again, in a module,
you have them in series

00:25:35.380 --> 00:25:36.940
and then these stacks
of cells in series

00:25:36.940 --> 00:25:38.856
are actually put in
parallel, but there's just

00:25:38.856 --> 00:25:41.670
an easy illustration.

00:25:41.670 --> 00:25:44.740
Again, cells in parallel,
you're matching in voltage

00:25:44.740 --> 00:25:47.580
and the currents
are what add in.

00:25:47.580 --> 00:25:51.190
And so if one cell let's say
has a low output voltage,

00:25:51.190 --> 00:25:57.375
it's going to shift
the operating power

00:25:57.375 --> 00:26:00.175
point for the other two cells
off of their maximum power

00:26:00.175 --> 00:26:05.660
point and you're going
to get a reduced output.

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:10.450
And so this is actually
very analogous to this idea

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:12.930
that when you make
your cells larger,

00:26:12.930 --> 00:26:15.930
generally their efficiency
and performance go down.

00:26:15.930 --> 00:26:18.046
You have a higher chance
of inhomogeneities

00:26:18.046 --> 00:26:20.420
and other things that might
detrimentally hurt your cell.

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:22.290
And this is kind of
analogous to saying

00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:25.470
when you hook a whole
bunch of cells in parallel,

00:26:25.470 --> 00:26:27.124
you're limited by
your worst cell.

00:26:27.124 --> 00:26:29.040
And in this case, you're
limited by your worst

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:31.690
region of that
cell, and so that's

00:26:31.690 --> 00:26:33.670
the same kind of analogy.

00:26:33.670 --> 00:26:35.540
And I think it's kind
of cool, and so you

00:26:35.540 --> 00:26:36.710
can see this for a lot
of different cells.

00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:38.550
So these are actually
getting pretty big.

00:26:38.550 --> 00:26:41.230
So when you're getting
to-- I don't know

00:26:41.230 --> 00:26:42.700
if they make cells this big.

00:26:42.700 --> 00:26:45.540
But it's 100 by 100.

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:46.545
That's a meter squared.

00:26:46.545 --> 00:26:48.170
Wow, so maybe Cad-tel
can get that big.

00:26:48.170 --> 00:26:48.920
Actually, they do.

00:26:48.920 --> 00:26:51.484
Look, here's First
Solar right here.

00:26:51.484 --> 00:26:52.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:53.935
PROFESSOR: I'm sorry?

00:26:53.935 --> 00:26:55.026
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:55.026 --> 00:26:56.650
PROFESSOR: Oh, OK.
[INAUDIBLE] modules.

00:26:56.650 --> 00:26:59.300
So some of the
cells you can see.

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:02.612
So here's cells--
amorphous, submodule.

00:27:02.612 --> 00:27:04.720
Anyhow, so the idea
is that you're, again,

00:27:04.720 --> 00:27:11.140
limited by your most
defective region in the cell.

00:27:11.140 --> 00:27:12.730
And again, illustrated
by this idea

00:27:12.730 --> 00:27:17.720
here is that if you take a cell,
you split it up into a grid,

00:27:17.720 --> 00:27:21.090
and you model it as a bunch
of many cells operating

00:27:21.090 --> 00:27:28.410
in parallel, you're again
limited by that bad region.

00:27:28.410 --> 00:27:33.010
And so this looks
a little outdated.

00:27:33.010 --> 00:27:34.940
So this is 2006.

00:27:34.940 --> 00:27:39.430
So this is cell performance
versus module performance,

00:27:39.430 --> 00:27:42.200
and you can see that it's
also quite significant.

00:27:42.200 --> 00:27:44.820
One of the other things
that's different about cells

00:27:44.820 --> 00:27:47.930
and modules is that you
have glass in front.

00:27:47.930 --> 00:27:50.754
So when you optimize--
for example, in class

00:27:50.754 --> 00:27:52.420
we optimized our
silicon nitride coating

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:55.680
for an air-silicon interface.

00:27:55.680 --> 00:28:00.720
Modules, you optimize at silicon
nitride coating for a silicon

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:02.320
to glass interface.

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:06.950
And the glass, which has an
index refraction of about 1.5,

00:28:06.950 --> 00:28:09.340
you're automatically going
to reflect 4% of the light,

00:28:09.340 --> 00:28:11.050
so that light's lost.

00:28:11.050 --> 00:28:13.270
But it does help with
your reflection losses

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:16.430
because you now have a
graded index of refraction.

00:28:16.430 --> 00:28:18.567
So it does reduce some of
those reflection losses

00:28:18.567 --> 00:28:19.400
from that interface.

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:19.899
Yeah?

00:28:19.899 --> 00:28:23.114
AUDIENCE: Is this just silicon?

00:28:23.114 --> 00:28:24.780
PROFESSOR: I'm guessing
yes because this

00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:26.250
is from Richard Swanson.

00:28:26.250 --> 00:28:27.547
This is Tonio's slide.

00:28:27.547 --> 00:28:29.630
My guess would be yes, but
don't quote me on that.

00:28:30.586 --> 00:28:34.897
AUDIENCE: So for the modules,
how is voltage and current

00:28:34.897 --> 00:28:35.397
controlled?

00:28:35.397 --> 00:28:37.757
I'm assuming that they control
it at a specific point.

00:28:37.757 --> 00:28:39.840
PROFESSOR: Yes, so that's
a great, great question,

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:40.340
actually.

00:28:40.340 --> 00:28:42.370
So your modules are
hooked up to an inverter.

00:28:42.370 --> 00:28:45.420
The output of your solar
cells are direct current,

00:28:45.420 --> 00:28:48.260
and so you have to convert
that to alternating current.

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:50.700
And the inverters are
actually rather intelligent.

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:53.831
They'll actually constantly scan
at a very high frequency where

00:28:53.831 --> 00:28:55.830
it should be operating
and taking the derivative

00:28:55.830 --> 00:28:59.032
and finding where
that optimal point is.

00:28:59.032 --> 00:29:00.865
And so one of the other
ideas is that if you

00:29:00.865 --> 00:29:02.630
have a bunch of
modules, usually those

00:29:02.630 --> 00:29:04.049
are also hooked up in parallel.

00:29:04.049 --> 00:29:05.840
And the idea is to have
instead of just one

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:09.190
inverter, a microinverter-- so
small inverters for each one.

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:11.960
So that way, each of those are
operating at the maximum power

00:29:11.960 --> 00:29:13.360
point.

00:29:13.360 --> 00:29:16.310
And I think problem is that
inverters are expensive

00:29:16.310 --> 00:29:17.930
and the larger
they are, generally

00:29:17.930 --> 00:29:20.710
the more efficient they
are and cheaper can be.

00:29:20.710 --> 00:29:24.675
So I don't know how far
that idea's been realized,

00:29:24.675 --> 00:29:26.127
but it's a good question.

00:29:26.127 --> 00:29:26.960
Does that answer it?

00:29:29.540 --> 00:29:33.280
So we have-- good,
plenty of time.

00:29:33.280 --> 00:29:37.710
So now we're moving
onto advanced concepts,

00:29:37.710 --> 00:29:40.952
which, again, area
that I'm working in.

00:29:40.952 --> 00:29:41.660
Kind of exciting.

00:29:41.660 --> 00:29:46.550
These are ideas that are
very, very high efficiency,

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:49.836
potentially very
low-cost, and that's

00:29:49.836 --> 00:29:50.960
kind of the allure to them.

00:29:50.960 --> 00:29:53.460
And they're great science
and research projects,

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:56.946
so they're really
exciting to be in.

00:29:56.946 --> 00:29:58.570
So one of things that
kind of motivates

00:29:58.570 --> 00:30:01.766
this work-- I think you guys
have seen this equation.

00:30:01.766 --> 00:30:02.890
I know I've used it before.

00:30:02.890 --> 00:30:07.410
But you know that the defining
metric for the performance

00:30:07.410 --> 00:30:09.310
of a cell in terms
of its economic cost

00:30:09.310 --> 00:30:13.100
is dollars per watt, so
dollars per watt peak.

00:30:13.100 --> 00:30:15.930
This is all defined at
your peak sun elimination.

00:30:15.930 --> 00:30:17.671
This makes it
location-blind, right?

00:30:17.671 --> 00:30:20.170
The really important thing when
integrating it onto the grid

00:30:20.170 --> 00:30:22.100
is how much are you
paying in terms of cents

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:22.880
per kilowatt hour.

00:30:25.480 --> 00:30:29.600
But to make it
location-blind, you

00:30:29.600 --> 00:30:32.252
put it into dollars per
watt, and dollars per watt

00:30:32.252 --> 00:30:33.460
is a function of many things.

00:30:33.460 --> 00:30:37.100
It's how much does it cost
to make the module itself?

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:40.030
So how many dollars
per given area?

00:30:40.030 --> 00:30:41.400
You divide it by the insulation.

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:42.900
For dollars per
watt peak, you'd set

00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:45.790
that to aim 1.5 or 1,000
kilowatts per meter squared.

00:30:45.790 --> 00:30:47.690
Multiply that times
your efficiency,

00:30:47.690 --> 00:30:51.190
and then by your yield, which
is a manufacturing parameter.

00:30:51.190 --> 00:30:54.980
So for some cells where if you
can reduce this number quite

00:30:54.980 --> 00:30:56.890
dramatically, so
for example, suppose

00:30:56.890 --> 00:31:00.100
you decide to go to very,
very thin wafers for silicon.

00:31:00.100 --> 00:31:03.690
You want to move to 20 micron
wafers, let's say, which

00:31:03.690 --> 00:31:07.220
is something that a lot of
companies now are working on.

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:09.792
What happens is that those
become very, very fragile.

00:31:09.792 --> 00:31:12.250
And when you handle them and
using all these pick and place

00:31:12.250 --> 00:31:14.166
operations to move them
to different processes

00:31:14.166 --> 00:31:16.870
within the cell fab,
oftentimes they'll break.

00:31:16.870 --> 00:31:19.257
And so that yield parameter
can come very important

00:31:19.257 --> 00:31:21.340
and [INAUDIBLE] interplayed
with this number here,

00:31:21.340 --> 00:31:22.990
and that's why it's there.

00:31:22.990 --> 00:31:25.851
So anyhow, what this
graph is is this

00:31:25.851 --> 00:31:27.540
is the dollars
per meter squared,

00:31:27.540 --> 00:31:30.500
so the cost of
producing that cell.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:32.990
And then you have
this efficiency here,

00:31:32.990 --> 00:31:35.980
and each of these
lines represents

00:31:35.980 --> 00:31:38.300
a certain dollars per watt.

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:41.800
And so I think the DOE has
wanted us to get to $1.00 per

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:44.909
watt, and you can do that by
either producing incredibly

00:31:44.909 --> 00:31:46.950
efficient cells, around
50%, which seems a little

00:31:46.950 --> 00:31:48.990
unreasonable.

00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:51.450
And they can cost $500
per meter squared,

00:31:51.450 --> 00:31:55.406
and that would be
actually a cheap panel.

00:31:55.406 --> 00:31:57.780
Or the other idea is to go to
very, very low cost and low

00:31:57.780 --> 00:32:00.810
efficiency, and you can try
to hover around in here.

00:32:00.810 --> 00:32:03.752
And so this nomenclature
I'm about to use

00:32:03.752 --> 00:32:06.210
is a little outdated, but I
think still some people use it,

00:32:06.210 --> 00:32:08.820
although rather loosely.

00:32:08.820 --> 00:32:11.220
What's known as
first-generation-- and again,

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:12.842
these terms I've
read papers now they

00:32:12.842 --> 00:32:14.550
claim that they're
third-generation where

00:32:14.550 --> 00:32:16.550
they used to be classified
as second-generation.

00:32:16.550 --> 00:32:19.300
It doesn't really matter,
but the ideas behind them

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:20.550
are still relevant.

00:32:20.550 --> 00:32:22.550
So the first-generation
with the single bandgap,

00:32:22.550 --> 00:32:25.499
it's crystalline silicon still
[INAUDIBLE] the market leader,

00:32:25.499 --> 00:32:27.540
and they're on the order
of 15% to 20% efficient,

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:29.580
but they're still
relatively high-cost.

00:32:29.580 --> 00:32:30.996
And there's actually
a lot of work

00:32:30.996 --> 00:32:33.980
now that says that this
can move in this direction,

00:32:33.980 --> 00:32:38.800
moving to thinner wafers,
increased laser processing.

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:43.170
Just tighter manufacturing can
really bring that cost down.

00:32:43.170 --> 00:32:45.495
So your second-generation
are your thin film.

00:32:45.495 --> 00:32:50.120
So this is either CIGS,
amorphous silicon, organics.

00:32:50.120 --> 00:32:52.830
A lot of these very, very
cheap to deposit, cheap

00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:54.510
to manufacture,
but they generally

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:58.210
suffer in efficiency, so they
hover around in this area.

00:32:58.210 --> 00:33:00.170
And so far, this
idea hasn't really

00:33:00.170 --> 00:33:02.170
fulfilled itself except
for maybe cad-tel,

00:33:02.170 --> 00:33:03.625
which is a thin film material.

00:33:03.625 --> 00:33:05.250
And then what we're
about to talk about

00:33:05.250 --> 00:33:07.340
is our third
generation of cells.

00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:11.640
So these are potentially
low-cost and potentially

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:12.585
incredibly efficient.

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:19.520
So we're going to talk about
only a few types today.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:20.700
I encourage you to look up.

00:33:20.700 --> 00:33:24.650
There's a whole different types
of solar cells you can look up,

00:33:24.650 --> 00:33:27.340
ideas, research being done.

00:33:27.340 --> 00:33:29.550
But I'm going talk--
this is what I work on,

00:33:29.550 --> 00:33:32.180
our intermediate-band
solar cells, specifically

00:33:32.180 --> 00:33:34.300
impurity-band photovoltaics.

00:33:34.300 --> 00:33:37.190
And I'm sure you're all
familiar with this picture,

00:33:37.190 --> 00:33:41.920
but if you want to create
free mobile charges

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:43.530
within your
semiconductor, you have

00:33:43.530 --> 00:33:46.180
to shine light on
it that has energies

00:33:46.180 --> 00:33:48.230
greater than the bandgap.

00:33:48.230 --> 00:33:52.480
And so you lose these
low-energy photons.

00:33:52.480 --> 00:33:54.957
They're not collected,
and what's a way

00:33:54.957 --> 00:33:56.040
that we can collect these?

00:33:56.040 --> 00:34:01.350
Well, one idea this
guy had was if you

00:34:01.350 --> 00:34:04.120
can create a material that
has a density of states that

00:34:04.120 --> 00:34:06.790
looks like this, you can
create a stepping stone

00:34:06.790 --> 00:34:09.654
by putting a half-filled
band within your bandgap that

00:34:09.654 --> 00:34:12.070
allows you to promote to that
band and then from that band

00:34:12.070 --> 00:34:13.330
into the conduction band.

00:34:13.330 --> 00:34:15.500
So the idea is that your
voltage output can still

00:34:15.500 --> 00:34:18.625
be maintained for
the host material,

00:34:18.625 --> 00:34:20.250
but you can collect
that extra current.

00:34:20.250 --> 00:34:22.679
So your ISC will
increase substantially,

00:34:22.679 --> 00:34:23.860
and so that's the promise.

00:34:23.860 --> 00:34:26.360
And if you do some theoretical
calculations similar

00:34:26.360 --> 00:34:29.900
what Shockley and Queisser did,
assuming the radiative lifetime

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:31.659
is your limiting
factor-- and again,

00:34:31.659 --> 00:34:34.560
that's certainly not the case
in some of the materials that

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:37.520
are worked on for this
idea-- and the idea

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:41.010
is you can actually get up
to around 63% efficient.

00:34:41.010 --> 00:34:44.194
And so what this graph is here,
here's your single gap limit.

00:34:44.194 --> 00:34:46.860
This is a calculation similar to
what Shockley and Queisser did.

00:34:46.860 --> 00:34:48.984
I think this is using
blackbody radiation, which is

00:34:48.984 --> 00:34:50.900
why the curves are so smooth.

00:34:50.900 --> 00:34:53.210
And it can actually
outperform a tandem cell,

00:34:53.210 --> 00:34:55.445
which is again a
multi-junction cell that

00:34:55.445 --> 00:34:58.410
are two cells stacked.

00:34:58.410 --> 00:35:01.090
And it turns out the
best is something

00:35:01.090 --> 00:35:03.810
that has a gap level
that's about 0.7 EV

00:35:03.810 --> 00:35:08.410
from the conduction band and
has a larger band gap, so

00:35:08.410 --> 00:35:11.520
that distance between
your valence band

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:16.490
and your conduction band of
around 1.9 electron volts,

00:35:16.490 --> 00:35:18.070
and that's kind of
the ideal material

00:35:18.070 --> 00:35:21.320
for an intermediate-band
solar cell.

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:23.480
So theoretically, this
idea is a great idea.

00:35:23.480 --> 00:35:26.930
Problem is, how do you
make a material that

00:35:26.930 --> 00:35:29.540
has this band structure?

00:35:29.540 --> 00:35:31.090
And that's really
the challenge where

00:35:31.090 --> 00:35:34.060
people are working right
now, and it's actually

00:35:34.060 --> 00:35:36.150
rather difficult. And so
there's three approaches.

00:35:36.150 --> 00:35:39.700
One is the impurity
band, which I personally

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:42.890
like because it's a
much cheaper method.

00:35:42.890 --> 00:35:45.390
Other one is this band
anti-crossing idea

00:35:45.390 --> 00:35:47.980
where you can actually
split the conduction band,

00:35:47.980 --> 00:35:50.660
and it's generally done with
these mixed metal oxides

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:52.160
and these highly
mismatched alloys,

00:35:52.160 --> 00:35:53.160
and they're really cool.

00:35:53.160 --> 00:35:56.100
And this is currently the
most successful material there

00:35:56.100 --> 00:35:57.570
for intermediate-band
solar cells.

00:35:57.570 --> 00:36:01.310
And then there's quantum dot
arrays and quantum structures

00:36:01.310 --> 00:36:04.930
that are also a possible
fabrication method.

00:36:04.930 --> 00:36:10.006
OK, so idea behind an
impurity photovoltaic

00:36:10.006 --> 00:36:12.130
is you start with let's
say a material like silicon

00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:14.100
or some other high-bandgap
gap semiconductor,

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:19.340
you put in impurities that
have these deep-level states.

00:36:19.340 --> 00:36:20.520
Iron would be an example.

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:22.270
So iron in very
low concentrations

00:36:22.270 --> 00:36:23.850
can be incredibly detrimental.

00:36:23.850 --> 00:36:25.467
But as you increase
that concentration

00:36:25.467 --> 00:36:27.050
above some critical
limit often called

00:36:27.050 --> 00:36:29.530
the [INAUDIBLE]
transition limit,

00:36:29.530 --> 00:36:34.280
you can actually form a
band within the bandgap.

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:37.180
And so the idea what's going
on here is that each of atoms

00:36:37.180 --> 00:36:40.190
this has some
electron wave function

00:36:40.190 --> 00:36:41.477
and some radius that it sees.

00:36:41.477 --> 00:36:43.310
And then as you increase
that concentration,

00:36:43.310 --> 00:36:45.000
these wave functions
overlap and you

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:48.960
can have conduction through
those mid-level states.

00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:51.880
So that's one
idea, and I like it

00:36:51.880 --> 00:36:54.680
because you use what I could
consider very dirty materials.

00:36:54.680 --> 00:36:56.790
The concentrations
you can put in here

00:36:56.790 --> 00:37:01.390
around are one atomic percent,
so your silicon's only 99.9%

00:37:01.390 --> 00:37:02.340
pure at this point.

00:37:06.186 --> 00:37:09.810
Other idea is to use either
quantum dots or these quantum

00:37:09.810 --> 00:37:10.310
wells.

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:13.760
So I think the idea here
is that these are localized

00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:15.290
and then this
becomes delocalized.

00:37:15.290 --> 00:37:19.895
So as you bring these quantum
well structures or quantum dots

00:37:19.895 --> 00:37:21.270
closer together,
you can actually

00:37:21.270 --> 00:37:23.390
get tunneling
through these states,

00:37:23.390 --> 00:37:25.150
and it basically
essentially forms

00:37:25.150 --> 00:37:27.740
a band within your bandgap.

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:29.242
Similar idea is to
do this locally--

00:37:29.242 --> 00:37:30.700
is that you have
one photon promote

00:37:30.700 --> 00:37:33.490
to one of these confined states
in your quantum structure,

00:37:33.490 --> 00:37:35.700
and then another photon
to keep promoting up

00:37:35.700 --> 00:37:40.004
into your conduction
band to create carriers.

00:37:40.004 --> 00:37:42.236
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
would there

00:37:42.236 --> 00:37:44.468
be quantum [INAUDIBLE]
embedded in the silicon,

00:37:44.468 --> 00:37:47.795
or these are solar cells
made out of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:37:47.795 --> 00:37:50.420
PROFESSOR: It's usually stacked
between two other semiconductor

00:37:50.420 --> 00:37:50.920
materials.

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:54.000
So you have semiconductor,
quantum dot, semiconductor.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:57.560
If you look up this paper
among-- if you look up

00:37:57.560 --> 00:38:01.940
anything-- so Antonio
Luque-- sorry, yeah.

00:38:01.940 --> 00:38:04.470
Luque and Marti are
two people in Spain

00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:07.249
who've kind of promoted a lot
of the theory around this.

00:38:07.249 --> 00:38:08.790
And look up their
quantum dot papers,

00:38:08.790 --> 00:38:10.430
and they'll really go
into the device structure

00:38:10.430 --> 00:38:11.110
if you're curious.

00:38:11.110 --> 00:38:12.410
I'd recommend doing that, Joel.

00:38:12.410 --> 00:38:16.206
AUDIENCE: So the x-axis
on these figures are--

00:38:16.206 --> 00:38:18.070
PROFESSOR: Real space.

00:38:18.070 --> 00:38:21.240
AUDIENCE: So there will be
some portions of the device

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:26.348
where this is possible in--
it kind of depends upon

00:38:26.348 --> 00:38:29.059
how many quantum
wells you actually

00:38:29.059 --> 00:38:30.058
put into your structure.

00:38:30.058 --> 00:38:32.224
PROFESSOR: Right, and that's
one of limiting things,

00:38:32.224 --> 00:38:34.640
is the EQE of these devices
because they can't grow

00:38:34.640 --> 00:38:37.157
so many are pretty limited.

00:38:37.157 --> 00:38:38.740
And again, these
also provide pathways

00:38:38.740 --> 00:38:40.114
for traps and
other things, which

00:38:40.114 --> 00:38:42.560
is again a huge problem
for these types of devices

00:38:42.560 --> 00:38:43.241
and ideas.

00:38:43.241 --> 00:38:44.740
And people are
working on that quite

00:38:44.740 --> 00:38:47.406
extensively from the theory side
and from the experimental side,

00:38:47.406 --> 00:38:49.865
and trying to merge the two.

00:38:49.865 --> 00:38:50.365
OK.

00:38:52.910 --> 00:38:53.859
Sorry, Ben?

00:38:53.859 --> 00:38:55.442
AUDIENCE: The quantum
well [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:55.442 --> 00:38:57.150
on the right, where
[INAUDIBLE] functions

00:38:57.150 --> 00:39:01.600
don't overlap, do those act
as recombination centers?

00:39:01.600 --> 00:39:04.640
PROFESSOR: It seems to me
that they would act as traps.

00:39:04.640 --> 00:39:08.210
Again, I'm not an expert on
these types of materials,

00:39:08.210 --> 00:39:10.940
but that would be
my inclination.

00:39:10.940 --> 00:39:13.360
I guess the idea is that you
have a very, very short well

00:39:13.360 --> 00:39:14.818
and then you have
a field across it

00:39:14.818 --> 00:39:17.720
so there's not something
else to hop to.

00:39:17.720 --> 00:39:20.061
And it just pulls it
right out, so that

00:39:20.061 --> 00:39:21.310
would be one device structure.

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:24.830
Again, these are generally
just like a few layers

00:39:24.830 --> 00:39:25.740
of quantum dots.

00:39:32.390 --> 00:39:34.135
Oh, I didn't put
up the [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:34.135 --> 00:39:35.760
So this is the
band-anticrossing model.

00:39:35.760 --> 00:39:38.720
So this is they're using
these quaternary alloys.

00:39:38.720 --> 00:39:40.979
So these are, again,
very, very hard to grow,

00:39:40.979 --> 00:39:42.770
and they've done these
awesome measurements

00:39:42.770 --> 00:39:45.700
where they can show your
valence band, conduction

00:39:45.700 --> 00:39:47.450
band, and your impurity
bands, and they're

00:39:47.450 --> 00:39:51.960
using a technique called
photomoduled reflectance,

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:55.860
so basically the reflectance
under oscillating fields.

00:39:55.860 --> 00:39:57.710
And from that, you
can get these kind

00:39:57.710 --> 00:40:00.506
of resonance points between
the different transitions

00:40:00.506 --> 00:40:02.630
and you can figure out
where your energy state lie.

00:40:02.630 --> 00:40:04.430
It's a really cool technique.

00:40:04.430 --> 00:40:06.520
But what they did is
they've done some very, very

00:40:06.520 --> 00:40:10.276
careful engineering and grown
these very, very carefully.

00:40:10.276 --> 00:40:11.650
And they can
actually demonstrate

00:40:11.650 --> 00:40:15.130
the sub-bandgap response
where if they have,

00:40:15.130 --> 00:40:18.420
let's say a photon that's
able to drive this transition

00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:20.890
but it's too low in energy
to drive that transition,

00:40:20.890 --> 00:40:22.300
they will get no current out.

00:40:22.300 --> 00:40:27.060
And then as soon as
they add the higher one,

00:40:27.060 --> 00:40:29.040
the current will increase.

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:32.560
And then if they turn off
that low-energy photon source,

00:40:32.560 --> 00:40:35.306
the current
decreases but doesn't

00:40:35.306 --> 00:40:37.180
stop because the other
high-energy photon can

00:40:37.180 --> 00:40:38.980
do both promotions.

00:40:38.980 --> 00:40:41.460
So this is actually one of
the only successful devices

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:43.280
of impurity-band
solar cells, and it

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:47.480
was quite an awesome feat.

00:40:47.480 --> 00:40:52.340
So I think one of
the few ones we'll

00:40:52.340 --> 00:40:55.740
talk about for another advanced
concept is hot carrier cells.

00:40:55.740 --> 00:40:59.420
This is something I think
Martin Green pioneered,

00:40:59.420 --> 00:41:01.810
and I believe it
still working on.

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:03.570
I haven't heard much
about them recently,

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:06.180
so I don't know what
the progress is there.

00:41:06.180 --> 00:41:08.580
So the idea is that one
of the biggest losses,

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:11.030
as I'm sure you guys know
from I think homework 1 or 2,

00:41:11.030 --> 00:41:13.200
is thermalization
in your solar cells.

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:15.890
When you promote an electron
well up into the conduction

00:41:15.890 --> 00:41:21.734
band, it then gives
off heat or phonons,

00:41:21.734 --> 00:41:23.400
which are just lattice
vibrations, which

00:41:23.400 --> 00:41:26.140
is another way of
thinking about heat.

00:41:26.140 --> 00:41:28.490
In that process, the problem
is that's incredibly fast.

00:41:28.490 --> 00:41:29.990
If you look at the
time scales here,

00:41:29.990 --> 00:41:32.240
so you come and you promote
this electron way up

00:41:32.240 --> 00:41:34.780
into your conduction band.

00:41:34.780 --> 00:41:37.090
This is what it looks like
prior at that promotion,

00:41:37.090 --> 00:41:40.450
and then it slowly decays,
and that decay happens over

00:41:40.450 --> 00:41:42.360
about a picosecond.

00:41:42.360 --> 00:41:45.722
So if you want to move your
carrier in a picosecond,

00:41:45.722 --> 00:41:47.180
if you know what
your field is, you

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:49.880
can see how long that length
is, and that length scale

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:51.700
is also incredibly short.

00:41:51.700 --> 00:41:57.220
And so one of the ideas
is, OK, how either we

00:41:57.220 --> 00:42:00.110
can decrease our path
length, or we can somehow

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:03.390
slow down thermalization,
and that's actually one idea.

00:42:03.390 --> 00:42:06.840
And to slow down
thermalization is something

00:42:06.840 --> 00:42:10.360
that they call carrier cooling.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:13.990
And basically making certain
types of device structures

00:42:13.990 --> 00:42:17.110
or material structures, you can
inhibit certain phonon modes.

00:42:17.110 --> 00:42:19.240
So when these
electrons get promoted,

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:20.410
they want to give off heat.

00:42:20.410 --> 00:42:22.201
They basically give
off lattice vibrations,

00:42:22.201 --> 00:42:24.280
so they want to shake
the atoms around them

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:28.430
and distribute that motion.

00:42:28.430 --> 00:42:30.410
If you prevent that
from happening somehow,

00:42:30.410 --> 00:42:33.840
through certain
types of structures,

00:42:33.840 --> 00:42:37.666
you can allow that
process to go slower,

00:42:37.666 --> 00:42:40.220
and that's one of the ideas.

00:42:40.220 --> 00:42:42.430
Extracting the carriers--
also kind of difficult.

00:42:42.430 --> 00:42:46.160
You need to have contacts
that are selective that

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:49.070
can take the hot carriers at
all the different energies

00:42:49.070 --> 00:42:51.070
that they're promoted
at, and that's

00:42:51.070 --> 00:42:52.740
also a really difficult idea.

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:54.823
And some of the ideas that
they've been working on

00:42:54.823 --> 00:42:57.510
are these resonant
tunneling contacts.

00:42:57.510 --> 00:43:00.780
So again, this is
kind of hairy stuff.

00:43:00.780 --> 00:43:02.284
I think these slides
are rather old

00:43:02.284 --> 00:43:04.200
and I don't know what's
come of this research.

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:08.200
So it's a really exciting
idea and I encourage

00:43:08.200 --> 00:43:11.840
you guys to look more into it.

00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:13.840
OK, so now we're going
to move a little bit away

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:17.739
from advanced concepts and talk
about kind of bulk thin film

00:43:17.739 --> 00:43:19.280
materials, and I
think we're actually

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:23.780
going to end quite
early, which is fine.

00:43:23.780 --> 00:43:30.280
So the most common
commercially-available type

00:43:30.280 --> 00:43:32.812
of material are these
wafer-based materials,

00:43:32.812 --> 00:43:34.270
so monocrystalline,
which you know,

00:43:34.270 --> 00:43:35.769
which is what our
cells are made of.

00:43:35.769 --> 00:43:37.760
This CZ, or Czochralski
growth, probably

00:43:37.760 --> 00:43:39.200
pronouncing that wrong.

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:41.616
Silicon,
multichrystalline silicon,

00:43:41.616 --> 00:43:43.990
which I think Tonio was showing
you what that looks like.

00:43:43.990 --> 00:43:45.910
You can see the
different grains.

00:43:45.910 --> 00:43:47.320
They're actually quite pretty.

00:43:47.320 --> 00:43:49.820
Ribbon silicon, which was
pioneered by Evergreen,

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:53.180
and I think now that
technology's gone.

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:55.680
Evergreen went out of
business, so I don't think

00:43:55.680 --> 00:43:58.090
that technology's still around.

00:43:58.090 --> 00:44:00.610
The [INAUDIBLE] still
might be making modules.

00:44:00.610 --> 00:44:04.264
Anyhow, so thin films.

00:44:04.264 --> 00:44:06.055
Cad-tel is still
currently-- or First Solar

00:44:06.055 --> 00:44:08.740
is still one of the
cheapest module makers.

00:44:08.740 --> 00:44:12.096
Their process was so cheap
that their efficiency really

00:44:12.096 --> 00:44:13.470
suffered because
they didn't even

00:44:13.470 --> 00:44:15.840
have an ARC coating for
the first 5 or 10 years

00:44:15.840 --> 00:44:16.700
of development.

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:18.908
And they said we didn't need
it, and they were right.

00:44:18.908 --> 00:44:20.890
They were still
outperforming silicon people.

00:44:20.890 --> 00:44:23.389
That's becoming less so the
case and one of the big problems

00:44:23.389 --> 00:44:26.840
with Cad-tel, as you guys
know, is the [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:26.840 --> 00:44:31.010
and also the toxicity,
which some people are

00:44:31.010 --> 00:44:33.931
really concerned about.

